I remember reading this as a child, but snow really changes the way a town feels. It's like you are exploring a brand new neighbourhood, that you have never been in before. Snow reveals things that are otherwise hidden and invisible, shows you secret you can't usually notice.
Is European coke like Mexican or like USA?

This is especially true for statues: when covered in snow, they look astonishingly different. They no longer represent some local minor historical figure, but something else - something abstract, alien, mysterious, rare.

Same for water fountains, gazebos, graveyards, stairs ...

I learned the word "sweetmeats" today, used for confection, sugar-rich foods, sweets, etc. I like it a lot, far better than the infantile-sounding "candy", I'm pretty sure if I was in an English-speaking country I would never eat anything sweet out of shame because of that word

"Sweetmeats" creates a far better mental image than any other word, it implies a solid consistency like flesh, chewiness, texture, nuance. A sweetmeat sounds like something prepared with mastership by a chef, or something you buy at a bazaar. Shame that it's an archaic word...

Snow is a mineral, just like diamonds and salt.

At the center of every snow crystal is a tiny mote of dust, which can be anything from volcanic ash to a particle from outer space.

It doesn’t snow much at the poles. Most blizzards there are made up of old snow blowing around.

Too much snow can drive a person crazy. Pibloktoq, a little-understood hysteria seen in people living in the Arctic, can cause a wide range of symptoms, including echolalia (senseless repetition of overheard words) and running around naked in the snow.

Symbolically the garden and the field are opposites even though they are deceptively similar at first glance... one is the Adamic space, the other - the Cainian

Both are natural space transformed by man, but the field is created for utility, the garden - for beauty, for God...

One is done out of necessity, the other has no practical purpose, it purely serves to our non-primal part, not the lizard brain that concerns itself only with survival. It shows esthetical sense, understanding. The garden is very illogical, useless, and this makes it holy.
